      {
        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "### Chemistry Insight\n\nThe unusually **low pKa₁ ≈ 1.2** reflects the strong electron-withdrawing effect of the adjacent carboxyl group, making oxalic acid one of the strongest organic diprotic acids. The relatively small gap between pKa₁ and pKa₂ (~2.6 units) is characteristic of short-chain dicarboxylic acids where the two acidic groups are in close proximity. These properties make oxalate (L²⁻) an excellent chelating ligand — the database lists complexes with **20 different metals** including Fe³⁺, Al³⁺, Ca²⁺, Cu²⁺, and UO₂²⁺.\n\n*Source: NIST SRD-46 (ligand_8872, metal_68)*",
